args: The capital... Never in my wildest dreams\ndid I imagine I would return here.

It WAS ruled by the iron fist of the Other
until recently. We couldn't simply stroll
on in. But now? I think we can get away
with a little recklessness.
After all, young Emile is the one sitting in\nthe seat of the emperor.
My experience with him in this world has\nyet to reveal an abundance of wisdom in\nthe boy. What about in yours?
A good question. Unlike his siblings,\nhe does not outwardly seem to possess\nthe same quick wit.
Then the fact that the city is deserted\ndoesn't look like it's down to a difference\nbetween the worlds.
In my travels, I had heard tell of its\nreputation, but...this is truly terrible.
There's hardly any human activity.\nI'd swear the place was in ruin if\nI didn't know better.
Well, it's little wonder. The new emperor\nis adept at inventing reasons to persecute.
There even seem to be some who believe\nthe reign of the previous emperor was\npreferable, oppressive though it was.
I'd hoped things would improve once they\nwere distanced from the Other's rule.
It beggars belief that the people could in\nfact look back fondly on such a dark time.\nYet another of my—
Yet another of your sins? Honestly,\nyou could do with a new schtick.\nThis one has worn out its welcome.
Though I certainly cannot imagine either\nyou OR Aurelius winning the award for\nFather of the Year.
...I have no retort. Yet that is all the more\nreason why I must take responsibility.
And just how to you intend to...\nHm? What's that?
Yes, perfect, right here! My statue is going\nto bring the taste level up around here by\nSEVERAL notches.
Oh, and I'm talking a HUGE one—I want\npeople to be able to see my immortalized\nface from anywhere in the city!
But this place isn't big enough to build\nsomething so large...
Then we just have to level the area!
You mean demolish all the houses here?!\nWhat about the people living in them?
EXCUSE me?! A bunch of termite-infested\nhovels or a BRILLIANT statue of me—can\nyou not grasp which is more important?!
Blast it, Emile! Just listen to yourself!
Steady, Audric. If you were to fly into\naction out there, you'd only make the\nsituation worse.
I know. Right now, I am merely a traveler.\nIf only there was someone who\nremembered my appearance... Hrm?
Will you leave this matter to me, sire?
I will be sure that the result is in keeping\nwith your heart's desire, Your Majesty.
It is an imperial decree. We must obey.
That name seems to ring a bell...\nAh, that's right! He was the knight in\ncharge of educating Emile as a boy.
Just so. He was appointed for his strong\nsense of justice and unbending morals,\nwhich we thought would do Emile good.
I can scarcely believe that he would meekly\nobey such a heinous order.
...I cannot leave things as they are.
Busy times are ahead, it would seem.\nBut for now, I—
Magnus. I did not appoint you as Emile's\ninstructor so that you would go around\ncleaning up his messes.
What? Who speaks? You would do well\nto bite your tongue ere you slander\nHis Majesty.
Have you no recollection of this face,\nMagnus?
Seeing a man who died long ago standing\nbefore you—looking tens of years younger,\nto boot—IS rather absurd.
The court magician, too?! And looking as\nshe did back then... Am I dreaming right\nnow?
You may think of it like that—as though\nyour former lord has come here from the\nworld beyond with a warning.
A warning... I see. I suppose if you really\nwere King Aurelius, you would not be able\nto overlook the state of the royal capital.
You seem well aware of it yourself.\nSo why do you lie indolent, Magnus?

You are an upright man who abhors
iniquity even more than I. I remember
you flaring up often about perfidy and
immorality.
That you remember my outbursts brings\nme deep shame.
You should feel nothing of the sort.\nThat uncompromising morality is why\nI entrusted Emile to your care.
And if you are the man you once were,\nyou more than anyone would be aware\nof the terrible state of this city.

Why do you balk at your duty to my son?
You are to provide remonstration, and if
necessary, guide him to his eternal rest
should you judge him beyond salvation.
Your king has asked you a question,\nMagnus. Silence will not be tolerated.
It is as if decades have turned back before\nmy eyes. I recall well being admonished\nby the former court magician.
Because you were even more obstinate\nthan Aurelius. I wanted to give you a\ntelling-off on more than one occasion.
Indeed I was... This truly takes me back.
And I. Yet we did not come here to\nrekindle old friendships. I ask for your\nanswer, Magnus.
It is because...I believe in him.
What is it you believe in?\nWhat do you see in my son?
I know what you mean to say. It is true\nthat Prince Emile is the most unlike His\nMajesty of any of his siblings.
You mean he lacks the talent to be a ruler?
That is a valid perspective, but...I believe\nthat he, more than any other, is well aware\nof that fact.
He feels keenly how powerless he is to\nact on his own.
Yet I believe that he possesses a\nresourcefulness as a ruler that even Your\nMajesty, the Wise King himself, did not.
And so you pinned your hopes on that\nability. Even so...
The people are suffering under Emile's\ntyranny. One can hardly call it governance.
I know that. I believe we should support\nhim until a sense of kingly duty sprouts\nwithin his heart.

Your loyalty is commendable, but we speak
of a young man who has no head for rule
in nothing less than the seat of the
emperor.
So long as he calls himself a lord of\nanything, Emile has a responsibility.\nOne he must shoulder himself.
And if he would not do so, then he has no\nright to preside over anything or anyone.

You are correct. Such is why I so dearly
respect you. Yet... How does the weight
of that judgment bear down on the bond
between father and son?
Emile wants, more than anything, to feel\nas though he will be all right. He is ever\nstruggling, ever desperate for help.
In such times, is it not a parent's role to\nsupport him?
...I do not recall commanding you to be a\nparent to him.
I do not claim the role so gleefully.\nBut what choice do I have if there is\nno one else to do it for him?
With all due respect, Your Majesty, the one\nwho was not enough for Emile...was you.
Speaking as the wise ruler you are, you\nassert correctly that a foolish ruler or a\ntyrant ought to be deposed.
But speaking as a father? You made the\nchoice to cut off your own son's future...\nand that is where I believe you are wrong.
